    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>So Which Is the 'Education Party'?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arthur A Ezra letter disputes August 14 article on issues facing Democrats at national convention in Los Angeles</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Democrats Ready the Stage for Their Post-Clinton Era'' (front page, Aug. 14):</p>
        <p>You say ''the Democrats call for increased financing for public schools, while the Republicans support taxpayer-financed vouchers to help parents pay for private schools.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Democrats Ready the Stage for Their Post-Clinton Era'' (front page, Aug. 14):</p>
        <p>You say ''the Democrats call for increased financing for public schools, while the Republicans support taxpayer-financed vouchers to help parents pay for private schools.''</p>
        <p>Since private schools cost much more than public schools, only those parents who can pay for the extra cost above the voucher value will be able to transfer their children to the private schools, leaving the others behind at the failing public schools.</p>
        <p>Even if the taxpayer-financed vouchers were to pay for the full cost of attending private schools, wouldn't all parents transfer their children out of failing schools?</p>
        <p>How could this be paid for after the tax cut advocated by the G.O.P.?</p>
        <p>ARTHUR A. EZRA  Huntington Station, N.Y.</p>
        <p>Aug. 15, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is dean emeritus of the School of Engineering Technologies, SUNY-Farmingdale.</p>
      </block>
